    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-05T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-05T04:00:00-05:00" n="779"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d779">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/11315</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Willard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Sebastian</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-05T10:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 5, 1918, 10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 2 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1772. Military attaché reports as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>September 3, 8 p.m. German Embassy distributed to pro-German and
                            subsidized press in Madrid this morning the text of the German answer to
                            Spain’s note. Naturally it will not be permitted publication. It is in
                            language as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>Germany will deliver to Spain an equivalent tonnage for all
                                    Spanish vessels illegally or unjustly sunk by her submarines;
                                    this, however, will be done only after a full and germane
                                    exchange of communications on the part of both Governments. The
                                    confiscation by the Spanish Government of any interned German
                                    vessel in its ports without any good reason for submitting the
                                    principal matters to a full and frank discussion of the merits
                                    of each individual case, will be considered by Germany as a
                                    cause for war. Lang.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Embassy as yet unable to confirm blockade report.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Willard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
